  description="Calculate your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) using standard formulas. Find your resting calorie needs."
  keywords="BMR calculator, basal metabolic rate, BMR calculator online, Mifflin-St Jeor, Harris-Benedict, Katch-McArdle, resting calories, metabolism calculator"
  canonicalUrl="https://calbmi.com/bmr.html"
  bodyClass="brand-bmr"
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "WebApplication",
      "name": "BMICalc - BMR Calculator",
      "url": "https://calbmi.com/bmr.html",
      "description": "Calculate your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) using Mifflin-St Jeor and Harris-Benedict.",
      "applicationCategory": "HealthApplication",
      "operatingSystem": "All",
      "browserRequirements": "Requires JavaScript. Requires HTML5.",
      "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "0.00", "priceCurrency": "USD" },
      "aggregateRating": {
        "@type": "AggregateRating",
        "ratingValue": "4.9",
        "ratingCount": "184",
        "bestRating": "5",
        "worstRating": "1"
      }
    }
    </script>
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [{
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) is the minimum number of calories your body needs to survive and perform basic life-sustaining functions—such as breathing, blood circulation, cellular production, nutrient processing, and body temperature regulation—when at complete rest in a temperate environment."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between BMR and TDEE?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "BMR represents the energy your body burns solely to stay alive at rest, without any movement. TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure) is your BMR plus all the calories you burn from daily movement, walking, working, eating, and exercise. TDEE is BMR multiplied by an activity level factor."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which BMR formula is the most accurate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The Mifflin-St Jeor equation is widely considered the most accurate formula for the general population. The Revised Harris-Benedict equation is also highly respected but tends to slightly overestimate BMR. For individuals with high muscle mass or low body fat, the Katch-McArdle equation is the most accurate because it calculates resting metabolism based on fat-free mass (Lean Body Mass)."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does body fat percentage affect BMR?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Muscle tissue is metabolically active, burning about 13 calories per kilogram (6 calories/lb) per day at rest, whereas fat tissue burns only about 4.5 calories per kilogram (2 calories/lb) per day. Therefore, a person with a higher percentage of lean muscle mass will have a higher BMR than a person of the same weight with more body fat."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How can I increase my BMR?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The most effective way to increase your BMR is by building muscle through resistance training (weightlifting, bodyweight exercises). Eating adequate protein also increases metabolic rate temporarily due to the thermic effect of food (TEF), and avoiding extreme calorie restriction prevents metabolic adaptation (starvation mode)."
        }
      }, {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does BMR decrease with age?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, BMR naturally declines as you age. This decline is primarily due to the loss of lean muscle mass (sarcopenia) that occurs with aging, as well as changes in hormone levels and physical activity. You can mitigate this decline by maintaining a strength training routine."
        }
      }]
    }
    </script>
